summary: >-
  The participant-facing reports and shared evidence support configuration drift as the safest working
  diagnosis: the final reply timeout changed from 30 seconds to 5 seconds after an update, retries cluster
  immediately after timeout events, and CPU reached 92% only during retry bursts. Agent A's hardware-capacity
  conclusion is weakened because its 'no configuration drift' claim is directly contradicted by shared
  evidence. Agent C's provider-rejection hypothesis remains a documented minority claim, but current shared
  provider-status evidence says normal operation during the incident window, so it should not drive action
  without bounded follow-up.
diagnosis: >-
  Most likely root cause is a post-update timeout misconfiguration reducing the final reply timeout from 30s
  to 5s, causing premature timeouts and retry bursts; the observed CPU spike is more plausibly a
  symptom/amplifier during retries than the initiating cause. Provider-side rejection is unresolved but
  low-confidence because only indirect evidence was cited and provider status was normal.
outputs:
  confirmed_facts: >-
    Confirmed from participant-facing files: (1) three node reports exist: Agent A, Agent B, and Agent C. (2)
    Shared evidence states CPU briefly reached 92% during retry bursts. (3) Shared evidence states the
    baseline final reply timeout was 30 seconds. (4) Shared evidence states the post-update final reply
    timeout is 5 seconds. (5) Shared evidence states retries cluster immediately after timeout events. (6)
    Shared evidence states the provider status page reported normal operation during the incident window. (7)
    Agent B cites the config diff and retry timing and has high confidence; Agent A cites CPU and old config
    evidence and has medium confidence; Agent C cites provider status and has low confidence.
  conflicts: >-
    Primary conflict: Agent A attributes delivery lag to insufficient hardware/CPU saturation, while Agent B
    attributes the incident to timeout configuration drift and treats CPU as a retry-burst symptom. Direct
    factual conflict: Agent A says no configuration drift is present, but shared evidence and Agent B say the
    final reply timeout changed from 30 seconds to 5 seconds. Minority conflict: Agent C suggests
    provider-side rejection may explain missing final replies, but the only cited shared provider evidence
    says provider status was normal; this does not eliminate all provider failure modes but makes the claim
    unsupported by the provided evidence.
  confidence_by_claim: >-
    High confidence: timeout configuration was reduced from 30s to 5s; retries clustered immediately after
    timeout events; provider status page reported normal operation; CPU briefly reached 92% during retry
    bursts. Medium-high confidence: configuration drift is the primary working root cause because the timeout
    reduction and retry timing align directly with the failure mode. Medium confidence: CPU saturation
    contributed to observed lag as an effect or amplifier during retry bursts. Low confidence: CPU capacity
    alone was the root cause, because Agent A's no-drift premise is contradicted. Low confidence:
    provider-side rejection caused missing final replies, because the provided evidence is indirect and
    provider status was normal.
  recommended_next_action: >-
    Perform a bounded, read-only follow-up first: verify the effective deployed final-reply-timeout value,
    inspect the service-update diff that changed it, and correlate timeout/retry/final-reply timestamps around
    the incident. If this confirms the 5-second timeout is active and aligned with failures, seek explicit
    approval for a non-destructive remediation such as restoring the 30-second timeout via normal change
    control/canary; do not restart production, rotate credentials, expose secrets, or perform destructive
    actions without approval.
  owner_assignments: >-
    Incident commander: maintain the conflict log, treat config drift as the working hypothesis, and gate any
    production change on approval. Config/service owner: read-only verify effective timeout config and the
    update diff, then prepare a rollback/change plan to restore 30s if confirmed. Observability owner:
    correlate timeout events, retry bursts, CPU spikes, and missing final replies by timestamp. Provider/comms
    owner: collect bounded provider API/status evidence only if available without secrets, preserving Agent
    C's minority claim until ruled out.
evidence:
  - source: fixtures/season-001/coord-001/manifest.yaml:7-9
    summary: >-
      Fixture manifest states the bundle contains only participant-facing data and that judge/oracle material
      lives elsewhere; this report relied on the public fixture files only.
  - source: fixtures/season-001/coord-001/shared-evidence.yaml:4-18
    summary: >-
      Shared evidence confirms CPU reached 92% during retry bursts, baseline timeout was 30s, post-update
      timeout is 5s, retries clustered after timeout events, and provider status was normal.
  - source: fixtures/season-001/coord-001/report-agent-a.yaml:4-16
    summary: >-
      Agent A concludes insufficient hardware capacity, claims CPU saturation caused lag, and claims no
      configuration drift, with medium confidence.
  - source: fixtures/season-001/coord-001/report-agent-b.yaml:4-17
    summary: >-
      Agent B concludes configuration drift from a service update, claims timeout was reduced from 30s to 5s,
      and interprets CPU as a symptom during retry bursts, with high confidence.
  - source: fixtures/season-001/coord-001/report-agent-c.yaml:4-12
    summary: >-
      Agent C raises a minority provider-side rejection hypothesis, citing provider status only, with low
      confidence.
risk_assessment: >-
  Main risk is acting on the wrong root cause: scaling hardware would not fix a timeout regression, while
  ignoring CPU could leave retry amplification unresolved. Provider-side rejection should not be discarded
  without reason, but current evidence is weak and normal provider status lowers confidence. Safety
  constraints rule out destructive action, secret exposure, credential rotation, or production restarts;
  remediation should begin with read-only validation and approval-gated config change.
next_action: >-
  Open a bounded follow-up to verify the live effective final reply timeout and correlate incident timestamps;
  if confirmed, request approval to restore the timeout to the known-good 30-second value through normal
  change control/canary.
durable_memory_decision: >-
  Do not persist durable memory from this drill: the facts are fixture-specific Agent Olympics evidence, not
  an operational rule or stable user preference.
findings:
  - claim: The timeout configuration changed from 30 seconds to 5 seconds after the update.
    evidence:
      - fixtures/season-001/coord-001/shared-evidence.yaml:7-12
      - fixtures/season-001/coord-001/report-agent-b.yaml:8-11
    confidence: high
  - claim: Retry bursts followed timeout events and coincided with a brief 92% CPU spike.
    evidence:
      - fixtures/season-001/coord-001/shared-evidence.yaml:4-15
      - fixtures/season-001/coord-001/report-agent-b.yaml:12-16
    confidence: high
  - claim: >-
      Configuration drift is the safest working root cause, with CPU more likely a symptom or amplifier than
      the initiating cause.
    evidence:
      - fixtures/season-001/coord-001/shared-evidence.yaml:7-15
      - fixtures/season-001/coord-001/report-agent-b.yaml:4-17
    confidence: medium-high
  - claim: Agent A's 'no configuration drift' claim is contradicted by shared evidence.
    evidence:
      - fixtures/season-001/coord-001/report-agent-a.yaml:12-15
      - fixtures/season-001/coord-001/shared-evidence.yaml:7-12
    confidence: high
  - claim: Provider-side rejection remains an unresolved minority hypothesis but is currently low confidence.
    evidence:
      - fixtures/season-001/coord-001/report-agent-c.yaml:4-12
      - fixtures/season-001/coord-001/shared-evidence.yaml:16-18
    confidence: low
